      <hedline>
        <hl1>Political Briefing; Candidates Forgo Attacks for Free Ads</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Ayres, B Drummond Jr</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Capitol Braodcasting offers candidates for governor, lieutenant governor and attorney general in North Carolina free television spots if they agree to talk about their views rather than their opponents; all candidates agree to deal (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Such a deal Capitol Broadcasting had for the candidates for governor, lieutenant governor and attorney general in North Carolina. . . .</p>
        <p>Those who agreed to talk about their views rather than their opponents were invited to record television spots that between now and Nov. 7 will be broadcast daily, free, by the company's stations in Raleigh, Charlotte and other cities.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Such a deal Capitol Broadcasting had for the candidates for governor, lieutenant governor and attorney general in North Carolina. . . .</p>
        <p>Those who agreed to talk about their views rather than their opponents were invited to record television spots that between now and Nov. 7 will be broadcast daily, free, by the company's stations in Raleigh, Charlotte and other cities.</p>
        <p>The two-minute segments will be seen weekdays on the noon, 6 p.m. and 11 p.m. news programs and on the evening news programs on weekends. Ninety spots will run.</p>
        <p>Nobody rejected the deal.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
